Dominion Resources Services, Inc. Law Department P.O. Box 26532, Richmond, VA 23261
December 21, 2012
Kimberly D. Bose, Secretary Federal Energy Regulatory Commission 888 First Street, N.E. Washington, D.C. 20426
Re: KINCAID GENERATION, L.L.C. Docket No. ER13-___-000
Dear Secretary Bose:
Kincaid Generation, L.L.C. ("Kincaid" or the "Company") hereby submits for filing its proposed revenue requirement for Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation or Other Sources ("Reactive Power") under its Rate Schedule FERC No. 2. Reactive Power is supplied by the Company's generation facilities under Schedule 2 of the PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. Open Access Transmission Tariff ("PJM Tariff").1 Kincaid's proposed Revenue Requirement is based on its current costs and is calculated consistent with the "AEP" methodology that the Commission mandated for all generators seeking recovery of Reactive Power costs.2
Kincaid requests an effective date of the first day of the month in which the Commission issues an order accepting Kincaid Rate Schedule FERC No. 2 for filing, which Kincaid anticipates will be on or before March 1, 2013. This is consistent with the treatment that the Commission has accepted for other Revenue Requirements for Reactive Power production in PJM.3
Kincaid discussed this filing with Commonwealth Edison Company ("ComEd") in advance of this filing in order to eliminate as many issues as possible and come to an agreement on the appropriate Revenue Requirement. Under PJM's Schedule 2, ComEd will be the principle customer of the service. Kincaid is pleased to inform the Commission that as a result of the discussions, Kincaid and ComEd came to an agreement that the appropriate annual Revenue Requirement is $1,100,000. Kincaid is authorized to state that ComEd does not oppose the annual Revenue Requirement proposed in this amount. The agreed upon annual Revenue Requirement of $1,100,000 is justified in the attached testimony and exhibits.
I. BACKGROUND Kincaid owns and operates a 1,158 MW base load coal-fired plant located in Kincaid, Illinois. Units 1 and 2 began commercial service in 1967 and 1968, respectively. The Kincaid units consist of cyclone fired, once-through boilers from Babcock & Wilcox and turbine-generators from Westinghouse. Both units are equipped with electrostatic precipitators to trap fly ash, selective catalytic reduction systems to reduce nitrogen oxide emissions and activated carbon systems to reduce mercury. Additionally, the Kincaid facility has two generator step-up transformers, is interconnected with the transmission system owned by ComEd at 345kV per a normally open bus tiebreaker, and is located within PJM. Kincaid Generation, L.L.C., a Virginia Limited Liability Company, is 99% owned by Dominion Kincaid, Inc., which is in turn a wholly-owned subsidiary of Dominion Energy Inc., ("DEI"). DEI owns the remaining 1% of Kincaid. DEI is a wholly-owned subsidiary of Dominion Resources, Inc. ("DRI"). DRI is a public utility holding company under the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 2005 and the owner of Virginia Electric and Power Company ("Dominion Virginia Power"), an electric utility company as defined in PUHCA ? 2(a)(3). Kincaid is an exempt wholesale generator under Section 32 of the Public Utility Holding Company Act of 1935, as amended. Kincaid Generation, L.L.C., 86 FERC ? 62,176 (1999). The Commission has previously authorized Kincaid to make market-based sales by order dated March 31, 1999 in Docket No. ER99-1696-006, under its tariff, Kincaid Generation L.L.C., FERC Electric Tariff, Original Volume No. 1.4 II. REACTIVE POWER SERVICE Kincaid and ComEd are parties to a Facilities Agreement ("FA") that provides the terms and conditions for interconnection and operation and maintenance of the facilities that interconnect Kincaid to the ComEd system. The FA also defines Kincaid's obligations to provide reactive power support. Sections 5.1 and 5.2 of the FA provide that Kincaid will operate the facility at the power factor and voltage levels reasonably prescribed by ComEd. Section 5.3 provides that in order to maintain transmission voltage levels at the levels prescribed by ComEd, Kincaid shall monitor and adjust the reactive output of the generators to maintain such transmission voltage levels. Section 5.4 of the FA provides that Kincaid shall operate the facility with its voltage regulators in operation. Section 5.2 of the FA provides that Kincaid will operate to the voltage levels provided in Exhibit VII to the FA that specify maximum and minimum voltage levels, and Kincaid shall operate its generators so as to follow ComEd's voltage schedule within generator capabilities.
Because ComEd will be the principal customer of Kincaid's Reactive Power service under both the FA and Schedule 2 of the PJM Tariff, Kincaid discussed this filing with ComEd in order to develop an agreed-upon revenue requirement and eliminate as many issues as possible prior to filing. As a result of those discussions, ComEd has authorized Kincaid to state that ComEd does not oppose the agreed upon annual revenue requirement of$1,100,000. Support for the annual revenue requirement is provided in the attached testimony and exhibits described below.
III. TESTIMONY AND EXHIBITS OF MR. JEFFREY E. CURRIER This filing incorporates the testimony of Kincaid witness Mr. Jeffrey E. Currier, Manager, Planning and Analysis in Dominion Virginia Power's Generation Financial Services Department. Mr. Currier describes the calculation of the revenue requirement for Reactive Power charges under PJM's OATT Schedule 2. Mr. Currier calculates a cost-based revenue requirement using a fixed capability component that recovers the portion of plant costs attributable to Reactive Power capability of the Facility ("Fixed Capability Component"). As discussed herein, Mr. Currier's testimony and exhibits support an annual revenue requirement of $1,235,028 and through discussions with ComEd, Kincaid has agreed to seek an annual revenue requirement in the amount of $1,100,000.
A. THE FIXED CAPABILITY COMPONENT Following the AEP methodology,5 Mr. Currier allocates a portion of plant costs to Reactive Power production based on a percentage of plant investment cost. His allocation of investment costs between energy production and Reactive Power production is based upon allocation percentages provided by the generator manufacturers. Mr. Currier uses plant accounting data to calculate the cost of providing Reactive Power service. Under the AEP methodology, these incremental costs, that is the additional costs incurred in order to manufacture and install equipment that produces Reactive Power in addition to real power, are allocated to Reactive Power production.
To determine the Fixed Capability Component of the Fleet revenue requirement, Mr. Currier multiplies the investment allocated to Reactive Power by a levelized annual carrying charge. Kincaid's use of a levelized annual carrying charge is consistent with Commission policy requiring rates that employ the levelized methodology (or non-levelized, as the case may be) to be consistent over the life of the rate. An adjustment for accumulated deferred income taxes ("ADIT") was included, resulting in a lower Fixed Capability Revenue Requirement.
Kincaid is a non-utility generator and therefore is not subject to traditional rate regulation. Therefore, to avoid potential issues regarding rate of return, Kincaid has incorporated in its annual carrying charge a rate of return and capital structure based on the percentages utilized for transmission service and ancillary services for ComEd, the owner of the transmission facilities with which Kincaid is interconnected. The Commission has elsewhere accepted the use of such proxies as an alternative to rate of return submission from merchant generators, including merchant generators that are affiliated with public utilities. See, e.g. WPS Westwood Generation, L.L.C., 101 FERC ? 61,290, at 62,167 (2002), Bluegrass Generation Co., LLC, 118 FERC ? 61,214, P 86 (2007), Calpine Fox, L.L.C., 113 FERC ? 61,047 (2005), Duke Energy Fayette, L.L.C., 104 FERC ? 61,090 (2003).
Mr. Currier determines the other carrying charge components, such as operations and maintenance, administrative and general, and property tax expenses from 2011 data consistent with the practice previously accepted by the Commission.6
Mr. Currier derives the cost of generators, exciters, step-up transformers and accessory electric equipment that produces Reactive Power from a detailed Asset list as of July 31, 2012. In addition, Mr. Currier calculates the costs of the balance of plant that produces the real power that is consumed during the production of Reactive Power. After subtracting the costs of equipment already allocated to Reactive Power production, Mr. Currier applies an allocation factor to the balance for each generator where data is available. The annual value of the fixed capability component is $ 1,235,028, which represents Kincaid's calculated annual Reactive Power Revenue Requirement.
IV. INCORPORATING THE FLEET REVENUE REQUIREMENT INTO PJM SCHEDULE 2 Kincaid's revenue requirement is contained in the attached Rate Schedule FERC No. 2. PJM's Schedule 2 provides that a generation owner must file its revenue requirement with the Commission before it is incorporated into the PJM OATT. Schedule 2 states that PJM "shall pay each generation owner an amount equal to the generation owner's monthly revenue requirement as accepted or approved by the Commission." Therefore, Kincaid is filing its revenue requirement for acceptance by the Commission and anticipates that, as with other generators, PJM will incorporate Kincaid's revenue requirement into Schedule 2, effective on the first day of the month in which the Commission issues an order accepting Kincaid's Rate Schedule for filing, which the Company anticipates will be on or before March 1, 2013.
V. MISCELLANEOUS No costs or expenses supporting the rates proposed in this filing have been alleged or judged in any administrative or judicial proceeding to be illegal, duplicative or unnecessary or demonstrably the product of discriminatory practices.
Kincaid does not have any other rate schedule on file that is being superseded or supplemented, and does not have any rate on file for a similar jurisdictional service. Accordingly, rate comparisons are not provided with this filing.
Kincaid is filing a new revenue requirement for its own Reactive Power capability. Because the Rate Schedule provides that PJM will pay to Kincaid its entire revenue requirement each month, no revenue comparison is necessary. Kincaid cannot provide a revenue comparison for the transmission customers of PJM who are located in the ComEd zone. Therefore, Kincaid respectfully requests waiver of the Commission's regulations requiring a comparison of the impact of the change in its rates on customers.
VI. CONTENTS OF FILING The following documents are included in this filing:
1. Kincaid Generation, L.L.C., Rate Schedule FERC No. 2 presenting the revenue requirement for Reactive Power (Attachment A);
2. Testimony and Exhibits of Mr. Jeffrey E. Currier, Manager, Planning and Analysis in Dominion Virginia Power's Generation Planning and Analysis Department, presenting Kincaid's Reactive Power Revenue Requirement (Attachment B); and
3. A List of Recipients (Attachment C).
VII. COMMUNICATIONS Please direct all communications concerning this filing to the following persons and include their names on the Commission's official service list in this proceeding:
Michael C. Regulinski, Esquire Assistant General Counsel Dominion Resources Services, Inc. P. O. Box 26532 Richmond, VA 23261 Telephone: 804/819-2794 Facsimile: 804/819-2183 E-Mail: Michael.Regulinski@dom.com
and
Nicole S. Allen Bruder, Gentile & Marcoux, L.L.P. 1701 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W. Suite 900 Washington, D.C. 20006 Telephone: 202/296-1500 Facsimile: 202/296-0627 E-Mail: nsallen@brudergentile.com A copy of this filing was served on PJM. In addition, copies of the filing were sent to representatives of the Commonwealth Edison Company. We thank the Commission for its consideration of this filing. Please direct any questions concerning this filing to the undersigned counsel.
Very truly yours,
/s/Michael C. Regulinski Michael C. Regulinski Counsel for Kincaid Energy L.L.C.

KINCAID ENERGY L.L.C.
RATE SCHEDULE FERC NO. 2
Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service
Kincaid Energy Center L.L.C. ("Kincaid") provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service ("Reactive Supply Service") from its generating facilities to the PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") system. This Rate Schedule sets forth Kincaid's revenue requirements for the provision of Reactive Supply Service to PJM, as contemplated by Schedule 2 of the PJM open access transmission tariff.
Kincaid's annual and monthly revenue requirement is set forth below. Total charges for any 12-month period will not be less than the sum of the annual charges specified below. This Rate Schedule shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
ANNUAL AND MONTHLY REVENUE REQUIREMENT:
Annual Revenue Requirement is $1,100,000 Monthly Revenue Requirement is $1,100,000 / 12 = $91,666.67

MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF
1. Availability: Seller makes electric energy and capacity available under this FERC electric tariff to any purchaser, except as prohibited below. Seller also makes available, to any purchaser, ancillary services except as prohibited below: a. New England. Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10- minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. b. PJM. Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10- minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. c. New York. Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. d. California. Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. e. MISO. Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. ("MISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. f. Third-Party Ancillary Services. Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental , and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of a public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability: This tariff is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity and ancillary services by Seller at market-based rates. 3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between Seller and the purchaser. 5. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff. 6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Seller has been granted the following waivers and exemptions in connection with its market-based rate authority: (i) waiver of Subparts B and C of Part 35 regarding the filing of rate schedules, except Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; (ii) waiver of the accounting and related reporting requirements under Part 41, Part 101, with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects, and Part 141, with the exception of Sections 141.14 and 141.15, of the Commission's regulations; and (iii) blanket authorization under Section 204 of the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. 824c, and Part 34 of the Commission's regulations to issue securities and assume obligations and liability. See Kincaid Generation L.L.C., 78 FERC 61,082 (1997). 7. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 2 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Northeast Region. Seller is a Category 1 Seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a), in the Southeast, Southwest, Southwest Power Pool, Central and Northwest Regions. 8. Effective Date: This tariff is effective upon the date specified by the Commission.
